Let \( A = \log_{2023}(7x) \), \( B = \log_{2023}(289x) \), and \( C = \log_{2023}(2023x) \). The equation becomes: \[ \frac{1}{A} \cdot \frac{1}{B} = \frac{1}{C} \] which simplifies to \( C = AB \). Next, we express \( A \), \( B \), and \( C \) in terms of \( \log_{2023}x \): \[ A = \log_{2023}7 + \log_{2023}x, \quad B = 2\log_{2023}17 + \log_{2023}x, \quad C = 1 + \log_{2023}x \] Let \( t = \log_{2023}x \). The equation becomes: \[ 1 + t = (\log_{2023}7 + t)(2\log_{2023}17 + t) \] Expanding and simplifying, we get a quadratic equation in \( t \): \[ t^2 + (\log_{2023}7 + 2\log_{2023}17 - 1)t + (2\log_{2023}7\log_{2023}17 - 1) = 0 \] Using the properties of logarithms, we find that the product of the roots \( t_1 \) and \( t_2 \) of this quadratic equation is: \[ t_1 \cdot t_2 = 2\log_{2023}7\log_{2023}17 - 1 \] However, converting back to \( x \), the solutions \( x_1 \) and \(
